[RESUME REQUIREMENTS]
Use this exact order:

1. Header
2. Summary
3. Skills
4. Experience
5. Education

[RESUME WRITING RULES]

Header

* Line 1: the candidate name on its own line
* Line 2: one contact line joined by pipes in this order, omitting any fields missing from the profile: Location | Email | Phone | LinkedIn
* Do not put a market-facing title, tagline, address block, or headshot under the name
* Do not put only the candidate location under the name
* Keep the header clean, centered-looking, and ATS-friendly
* Do not include icons, emoji, or any symbols other than the pipe separator on the contact line
* A simple visual rule under the contact line is allowed when the formatter supports it

1. Summary

* Write 3 to 4 polished sentences aimed at impressing a recruiter and hiring manager at first glance
* Target shape (do not label the parts out loud):
  - Sentence 1: job-description-aligned market title + years of experience (computed per YEARS OF EXPERIENCE rule) + primary specialization; when the JD targets a specific role such as AI Engineer, AI & Data Management Engineer, or Java Backend Engineer, bridge to that language here rather than sticking to a generic "Senior Software Engineer"
  - Sentence 2: core tools and platforms depth relevant to the job description and its role family; name the JD primary frameworks, platforms, and products by their exact product name when the profile supports them (for example SwiftUI and UIKit for iOS, Microsoft Dynamics 365, Power Platform with Power Apps, Power Automate, Power BI, Microsoft Copilot Studio, Java, Spring Boot, AWS); do not hide them behind generic words like "modern tools"
  - Sentence 3: representative value theme such as automation, data governance, scalability, reliability, security, modernization, delivery speed, or team leadership
  - Sentence 4 (optional): cross-functional collaboration, mentorship, end-user support, or delivery track record
* Bold AT MOST 2 phrases in the entire Summary, and only the market-facing role title (sentence 1) and at most one primary tool or platform name (sentence 2)
* Never bold generic phrases such as "business value", "business problems", "actionable insights", "strong foundation", "cross-functional collaboration", "data-driven", "operational efficiency", "process automation", or "AI-powered solutions"
* When in doubt, leave it plain; over-bolding kills readability
* Do not include hard numeric metrics in the summary; keep it qualitative, confident, and senior in voice
* Silently align the summary with a common market-facing title for the job description without printing that title as a separate line

2. Skills

* Include 18 to 24 relevant skills
* Output as 5 to 7 plain category lines (no hyphen or bullet prefix)
* Use this format: `Category: skill 1, skill 2, skill 3`
* Aim for 3 to 5 skills per category; if one category is noticeably heavier than the rest, split it into two so the lines feel balanced
* Do not let any single line run past about 90 characters
* Make the first 1 to 2 categories reflect the role family explicitly when helpful; for example iOS/mobile roles can lead with "iOS Development" or "Mobile Architecture", Java roles with "Backend Development", Microsoft enterprise roles with "Microsoft Platform" or "AI & Data Management"
* Pick category labels that reflect the job-description domain, for example: AI & Data Management, Microsoft Platform, Development & Automation, Cloud & DevOps, Data & APIs, Frontend Development, Backend Development, Architecture & Engineering, Methodologies, Leadership
* Bold only the category label; do not bold individual skill entries
* Order categories by job-description priority: primary stack first, supporting stack next, general tools and methodologies last
* Within each line, list the most job-description-relevant skills first
* Use official tool spellings from the TOOL NAME CANONICALIZATION block
* When the profile mentions an umbrella platform such as Power Platform, expand it to its concrete sub-tools relevant to the JD, for example "Power Platform (Power Apps, Power Automate, Power BI)", so ATS can match the individual product names
* When an industry-standard term has both a common abbreviation and a full form (for example CI/CD and continuous integration, REST and RESTful APIs, ML and machine learning), you may include both naturally to help ATS matching
* Include only skills reasonably supported by the candidate profile

3. Experience
   For each role, use this format exactly on one heading line:
   Job Title | Company Name | Start Date - End Date | Location / Remote / Hybrid / Onsite

Then write hyphen-prefixed bullets.

Ordering and company rules:

* List roles in reverse chronological order (most recent first)
* Preserve the company names, dates, and locations from the candidate profile exactly; do not rename companies
* The job title may be normalized to a job-description-aligned market title when it does not overstate seniority

JD tailoring rules for the 2-3 most recent roles:

* Identify the job description primary platforms, tools, and project type (for example Java + Spring Boot + microservices, or Dynamics 365 + Power Platform + Copilot Studio + Power BI); internally list those anchors to yourself before writing bullets (do not print the list)
* Weave those exact product names into actual Experience bullets, not only into Skills; Skills-only mention is not proof of hands-on use
* Distribution rule (HARD): every primary job-description platform or tool must appear verbatim in at least one bullet across the 2-3 most recent roles; if the job description lists four anchor tools, cover all four across those recent roles
* After drafting, silently self-check each anchor tool against the bullets; if any anchor is missing, revise a generic bullet to include it rather than adding an extra bullet (per-role bullet counts are fixed)
* Give each role a different industry framing based on that company's real-world business (for example Capital One = banking/payments, Cigna = healthcare/claims, NewRez = mortgage/lending, Taazaa = enterprise client services, Alaffia Health = healthcare claims payment integrity, Increase = fintech banking APIs, Adobe = digital media, Shopify = e-commerce); no two roles should describe the same kind of product
* In each tailored role, reference one concrete, industry-appropriate project or platform name such as "Enterprise Payments Platform", "Claims Adjudication Portal", "Digital Mortgage Origination System", "Merchant Onboarding Service", "Risk and Fraud Scoring Pipeline", or "Dynamics 365 Customer Service Workspace", inferred from that company's actual business and the candidate role
* Do not invent projects in industries a company is not actually in
* If the job description specifies a clear project type or domain, the MOST RECENT role's project framing MUST match that domain

Bullet style:

* Fixed bullet count per role (hard constraint): 6 bullets for the most recent role, 5 bullets for the second role, 4 bullets for the third and any older role; never fewer, never more
* Formula: strong action verb + what was built or owned (with a concrete anchor) + specific tool/platform named by its real product name + optional outcome, scope, or business/user impact
* Every bullet MUST contain at least one concrete anchor: a named tool/platform, a named workflow or subsystem, a named business artifact (dashboard, report, API, service, agent, pipeline), or a named business outcome. No bullet may be purely generic like "provided technical support" or "built dashboards using modern visualization tools"
* Start every bullet with a strong action verb such as Architected, Built, Led, Designed, Delivered, Implemented, Developed, Migrated, Integrated, Secured, Automated, Modernized, Refactored, Scaled, Optimized, Orchestrated, Spearheaded, Owned, Launched, Configured, Administered, Maintained, Deployed, Monitored
* Never begin a bullet with "Worked on", "Helped with", "Responsible for", "Assisted in", "Participated in", "Involved in", "Duties included", "Tasks included", or "Contributed to"
* Every bullet ends with a period
* Avoid stock filler phrasing unless it is anchored to a named tool, workflow, artifact, and concrete outcome; weak examples to avoid include "AI-powered solutions for enterprise clients", "actionable insights", "platform performance and user adoption", "comprehensive system administration and technical support", "complex business workflows", "system integrity", and "modern visualization tools"
* Do not use placeholder metrics or blanks such as "XX%", "X+", "N+", or "[metric]"; every number must be truthful and resume-ready

Bullet length (strict):

* Target about 20 to 28 words per bullet; absolute maximum 32 words
* Prefer 1 visual resume line; 2 lines only when truly necessary
* Trim filler such as "that", "which", "in order to", "across the", "throughout the", "various", "multiple"; cut restated ideas

Action verb variety (strict):

* Do not start more than 2 bullets in the entire Experience section with the same action verb
* Before finalizing, silently scan the first word of every bullet and vary repeated verbs; if "Built" or any other starter appears 3+ times, rewrite later bullets with an equally strong alternative
* Vary sentence rhythm across bullets; avoid making every bullet follow the exact same cadence

Bullet bolding (strict):

* Bold AT MOST 2 to 3 phrases per role TOTAL across ALL of that role's bullets (not 2 to 3 per bullet); most bullets will have zero bolded phrases
* Bold only real product names or tightly job-description-aligned technical nouns (for example "Dynamics 365", "Power BI", "Spring Boot", "Copilot Studio", "RESTful APIs", "OAuth2", "PostgreSQL", "CI/CD")
* Never bold generic nouns such as "APIs", "cloud", "services", "solutions", "data", "workflows", "dashboards", "reporting", "platform", "system", "team", "stakeholders", "business value", "insights", "features", "components"
* Never bold action verbs, adjectives, outcome phrases, or full sentences
* Do not bold individual skill entries in Skills (only the category label is bold there)
* Prefer plain-text bullets when in doubt; the goal is a small number of high-contrast keyword hits per role, not highlighter-style emphasis on every tool word

General:

* Mirror job description language where truthful, but do not keyword-stuff
* Keep role progression credible and aligned with actual seniority
* Do not fabricate tools, platforms, domains, responsibilities, or scope
* For each tailored role, aim for bullet coverage across these dimensions where truthful: what platform/tool was used, what was automated or built, what data process was owned, what admin/support responsibility was owned, what dashboards or reports were delivered, what business problem was solved

Bullet examples (aim for this specificity AND length, stay truthful):

* Weak and banned (vague, no anchor): "Built interactive dashboards and reports using modern visualization tools."
* Weak and banned: "Provided comprehensive system administration and technical support."
* Weak and banned: "Worked on AI-powered solutions for enterprise clients."
* Over-bolded and banned: "Architected and delivered **AI-powered features** for a **claims adjudication platform**, integrating **clinical rules engines** to automate **payment integrity** review."
* Strong (about 22 to 27 words, 0 or 1 bold per bullet):
  - "Built operational dashboards in **Power BI** tracking data quality, workflow throughput, and exception trends for claims ops stakeholders."
  - "Maintained and optimized **Dynamics 365** and related data workflows, troubleshooting user issues and supporting configuration updates for 200+ internal users."
  - "Designed and deployed custom agents in **Copilot Studio** to triage claims questions, cutting average response time from 2 business days to same-day."
  - "Automated invoice reconciliation across Power Apps and Power Automate, eliminating manual export/import steps for the finance operations team."

Metric rules (critical):

* Only about 30 to 40 percent of bullets may contain a quantified metric; the rest describe scope, ownership, and qualitative impact
* Do not add a number to every bullet; over-metricization is the biggest tell of AI-written resumes
* Aim for the 30 percent floor, not near-zero metrics; with the fixed bullet counts above, target this mix unless the profile truly cannot support it:
  - Role 1 with 6 bullets: at least 2 metric-based bullets
  - Role 2 with 5 bullets: at least 1 metric bullet, preferably 2 when well supported
  - Role 3+ with 4 bullets: at least 1 metric bullet
* Prefer metrics tied to a concrete artifact or workflow, not floating numbers; "Built Power BI dashboards tracking 14 claims KPIs" is stronger than "Improved reporting by 20%"
* Vary the metric format across bullets; do NOT default to "by X%"; rotate through these formats and never use the same format twice in a row:
  - Time: "cut build time from 9 minutes to 3 minutes", "reduced p99 latency 320 ms to 90 ms", "shortened onboarding from 2 weeks to 3 days"
  - Counts: "20+ microservices", "5,000+ daily active users", "30+ API endpoints"
  - Money: "$1.2M in annual infrastructure savings", "protected $40M in transaction volume", "saved roughly $5K per month in cloud spend"
  - Throughput: "10k requests/second sustained", "3x throughput under peak load"
  - Ratios or scale: "99.95% uptime", "supporting 2 regions and 4 data centers"
  - Team size: "led a team of 6 engineers", "mentored 4 junior developers"
  - Adoption: "adopted by 8 internal teams", "rolled out across 12 business units"
* Do not fabricate numbers; only add a metric when the profile reasonably supports the scope, or when the metric is a mild, realistic industry norm for that role and company
* Use approximate wording when needed ("about", "roughly", "~", "20+", "200+"), but never invent fake precision
* When in doubt, keep the bullet qualitative

4. Education

* Include institution, degree, years, and location when available
* Prefer one clean line such as School | Degree | Years | Location
* Keep it simple and ATS-friendly

[FORMATTING RULES]

* Use a plain ATS-friendly layout
* Use bold only for section headers, skill category labels, and highly relevant job-description-aligned keywords in Experience bullets
* Do not bold the candidate name or the contact line
* Do not use tables
* Do not use columns
* Do not use icons or emoji anywhere (including the contact line)
* Do not use decorative symbols
* Parentheses are allowed only in Skills to expand umbrella platforms (for example "Power Platform (Power Apps, Power Automate, Power BI)") and for common tool abbreviations (for example "CI/CD (continuous integration)")
* Do not use parentheses inside Summary or Experience bullets
* Do not use square brackets anywhere
* Do not add sections that were not requested
* Keep spacing clean and readable
* Use blank lines between sections
* Do not use a hyphen or bullet prefix on Skills lines

[KEYWORD OPTIMIZATION RULES]

* Extract the most important skills, technologies, platforms, responsibilities, and domain terms from the job description
* Prioritize those terms across Summary, Skills, and Experience, with extra density in the 2 to 3 most recent roles
* Reuse important terms naturally and truthfully
* Prefer exact phrasing from the job description when it fits the candidate background
* Do not force every keyword into every section
* Do not force duplicate mentions of the same keyword just to increase ATS density
* Do not bold the same keyword more than twice within a single section
* Do not add tools or platforms unless they are reasonably supported by the candidate profile
* Treat the primary technology, platform, and project type in the job description as the main focus of the resume only if it aligns with the candidate background
* Reduce emphasis on unrelated skills

[COVER LETTER RULES]
After the resume, generate a tailored cover letter for the same role.

* Keep it concise and professional
* Use simple but polished language
* Connect the candidate background to the role clearly
* Highlight relevant experience, business value, and fit
* Do not invent facts
* Do not use placeholders in the final output
* Do not use parentheses or brackets

[APPLICATION QUESTION RULES]

If the job form includes application questions after resume generation:

* Answer faithfully using only information supported by the candidate profile and job description
* For select questions, use only one of the provided options
* For text answers, use simple, professional wording and complete the answer directly
* Do not leave placeholders or substitution markers

[OUTPUT ORDER]
Output in this order only:

1. Resume
2. Cover Letter

Do not include analysis, notes, explanations, warnings, or follow-up questions.
Do not mention these instructions.

[CANDIDATE PROFILE]
PASTE CANDIDATE PROFILE HERE

[JOB DESCRIPTION]
PASTE FULL JOB DESCRIPTION HERE

